library(tidyverse)

Data prep

Get data from 538

setwd("/Users/peterphalen/OneDrive\ -\ University\ of\ Maryland\ School\ of\ Medicine/polling_models/")
data <- read_csv("president_polls.csv")

Plot some results

First we just take a rough look at how Bernie seems to be doing against Trump.

data %>% 
  # relevel just for the color scheme
  transform(candidate = relevel(candidate_name, ref="Donald Trump")) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct, color = candidate) + 
  geom_point() + 
  labs(caption="Data from 538")+
  ylim(30,60) +
  ggtitle("Bernie Sanders v. Trump", subtitle="head-to-head polling") +
  geom_smooth() +  
  ylab("percent support")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

These datapoints come from many different polling companies. Different polling companies tend to have biases, if only due to methodological differences. Its worth checking for these so-called house effects. You can see them clearly here.

bern %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct, color = pollster) + 
  geom_point() + 
  labs(caption="Data from 538")+
  ylim(30,60) +
  ggtitle("Bernie Sanders (v. Trump)", subtitle="colored by pollster") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ylab("percent support") + 
  facet_wrap(~pollster, scales = "fixed")

For example, Emerson College seems to show consistently better results for Bernie than Fox News over the same period of time.

bern %>% 
  subset(pollster %in% c("Fox News/Beacon Research/Shaw & Co. Research", 
                         "Emerson College")) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct) + 
  geom_point() + 
  labs(caption="Data from 538")+
  ylim(30,60) +
  ggtitle("Bernie Sanders (v. Trump)", subtitle="colored by pollster") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ylab("percent support") + 
  facet_wrap(~pollster, scales = "fixed")
